{"questionId":"9069519","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The overall equation for the production of hydrogen cyanide, HCN, is shown below.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">CH<sub>4</sub> (g) + NH<sub>3</sub> (g) +<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>O<sub>2</sub> (g) → HCN (g) + 3H<sub>2</sub>O (g)</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Identify the number of sigma and pi bonds in HCN.</p>\n<p><img src=\"__IMG__/e23002b73f8f4510a4c5b14aa6680faf9573be41.png\"></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>Sigma (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>σ</mtext></math>): 2 <em><strong>AND</strong> </em>Pi (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></math>): 2 ✔</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9069519","referenceCode":"22M.2.hl.TZ2.b(ii)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Identify the number of sigma and pi bonds in HCN.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b(ii)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 14: Chemical bonding and structure","14.1 Covalent bonding and electron domain and molecular geometries","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 14: Chemical bonding and structure"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}